I looked up &quot;curmudgeon&quot; in the OED, Grummanm, and I had
to laugh out loud because for some centuries it appears that
lexicographers have believed that the etymology of
CURMUDGEON was CORN HOARDER.

The OED notes the correction:

The occurrence in Holland's Livy, 1600, of CORNMUDGIN (q.v.)
has led to a suggestion that this was the original form, with the
meaning concealer or hoarder of corn, mudgin being associated
with ME. much-en, mich-en to pilfer, steal, or muchier, Norman
form of OF. mucier, musser to conceal, hide away. But examination
of the evidence shows that curmudgeon was in use a quarter of a
century before Holland's date, and that cornmudgin is apparently
merely a nonce-word of Holland's, a play upon corn and curmudgeon.

Here's the CORNMUDGEON citation:

1600 HOLLAND Livy IV. xv. 150 A rich corne-mudgin [L. frumentarius],
that with a quart (or measure of corne of two pounds) had bought the
freedome of his fellow cittizens. Ibid. XXXVIII. xxxv. 1004 The
fines that certeine cornmudgins [L. frumentarios] paid, for hourding
up..their graine.

In fact, here are the OED citations prior to 1600 which show that
curmudgeon--contrary to the OED editors--could well be from CORN
HOARDER:

1. 1577 STANYHURST Descr. Irel. 102/2 in Holinshed, Such a clownish
Curmudgen.

Clownish curmudgeon is neutral although Jonson did make the point
that a corn hoarder can be a clown--or an eccho--in Every Man Out
of His Humor.

2. 1593 NASHE Christ's T. 85b, Our English Cormogeons, they haue
breasts, but giue no suck.

Nashe spells it COR-mundgeon and gives it the sense of &quot;hoarder.&quot;

3, 1604 T. WRIGHT Passions v. 289 Why do covetous cormogions
distill the best substance of their braines to get riches.

More sense of &quot;hoarding.&quot; Could it be Wright--who also uses
COR-mogion--is referring to the process of distilling malt from barley
which was also called corn or barley-corn?

Maybe the tradition that the Corn Hoarder died from a bout of
alcoholism comes from that etymological association.

It seems that the OED editors--who must have time on their hands--
have prepared a little pun:

The suggestion that the first syllable is cur, the dog, is perhaps
worthy of note;

Where's the usual citation? I don't see anything that suggests &quot;dog&quot;
between 1577 and 1600 and how is a &quot;dog&quot; a &quot;miser?&quot;

but that of Dr. Johnson's unknown correspondent, cur méchant
for F. méchant cur, evil or malicious heart, is noticeable only as
an ingenious specimen of pre-scientific etymology, and as having
been retailed by Ash in the form, from the French cur unknown,
and mechant a correspondent!

Exclamation point theirs.

Cur in English comes from the ME corre; canis villaticus, domesticus
probl from kurre, or korre from SW and Norw. dog. The OED shows
no French etymology for &quot;cur.&quot;

I can't believe that the OED editors would reconstruct the
etymology of a definition to make a little &quot;dog&quot; pun on
cur méchant. They must be really bored.

