exists from that time that says that Shakespeare was &quot;hoarding&quot;
corn or malt or anything else. There is one documents that shows
him *owning* 10 quarters of malt, but citizens were allowed to have
on hand enough grain each person in their household to live on for one year.

From the government's publication, &quot;A New Charge&quot; (1595), where town
officials were told to inspect the grain holdings of its inhabitants,
&quot;...allowing to every householder for his expenses in his house, for
every person thereof according to their quality, sufficient corn for bread
and drink between this and the next harvest, and for their seed after the
rate of their sowing of that country upon an acre.&quot;

Here is what Eccles says concerning Shakespeare's 10 quarters of malt:

&quot;This was a normal supply for household use; the schoolmaster,
Mr. Aspinall, had 11 quarters, and the vicar, Mr. Byfield, had six of
his own and four of his sister's.&quot; (Shakespeare in Warwickshire, p91).

Here is William Harrison's description of his household brewing

&quot;Nevertheless, sith I have taken occasion to speak of brewing, I will
exemplify in such a proportion as I am best skilled in, because it is
the usual rate for mine own family, and once in a month practised
by my wife and her maid-servants, who proceed withal after this
manner, as she hath oft informed me. Having therefore ground eight
bushels of good malt upon our quern, where the toll is saved, she
addeth unto it half a bushel of wheat meal, and so much of oats small
ground.... etc.&quot;

8 bushels, or 1 quarter per month, on an income of 40 pounds a year (Harrison
was a chaplian and a rector, not a wealthy man like Shakespeare). Since
the government would have allowed Harrison (if he had been alive in 1595)
a one year supply of malt, he would have been allowed 12 quarters.

Shakespeare was not a &quot;corn hoarder&quot;. He was a concerned family
man who ensured that the members of his household had sufficient
grain on hand to survive for a year in the event of his sudden death,
a common occurrence at that time, or even if he was merely detained
